      "content": "The decline wasn't just about corporations or deregulation; it was a deliberate strategy by the Reagan and Bush administrations to dismantle the very power unions had built, which they viewed as a threat to free markets. While critics argue unions slow down efficiency, the historical record shows that strong collective bargaining actually drives productivity by forcing companies to invest in better technology and training to compete. Without unions, the US economy would likely face higher unemployment and lower wages, as workers would lack the leverage to demand fair pay and safe working conditions.",
